rComments: Prof Frederiksen change my mind of learning global geo. Her lecture is interesting and easy to understand, she came up with key points and full of class discussion, make it earlier to understand concepts and knowledges. Great prof will to taking her course again!

Prof. Frederiksen is what you want in a Prof. Scary smart, knowledgable, nice but not too nice. The course is spacey, as the name suggests. Sometimes I wondered if all those giant words were necessary, but I guess it comes with the "territory ". (Ha ha) Well worth taking.

I like Prof. Frederksen. She has an interesting accent, maybe Californian? I know it's not important, but it's what struck me most about her at first. The course was a little mind boggling at times, mostly because of all the terms and jargon, sometimes about basic ideas that were made to seem more difficult . TA's drop F bombs.. a bit odd to me.

Undoubtedly one of the best profs I've had at U of T. Like the others have said, her lectures are so engaging and she really connects with her students. Unfortunately the TA strike in 2015 screwed everything up and halted the lectures halfway through the course. Nonetheless things were great while they lasted!

A super engaging teacher with with very positive energy. She continually asks for feedback from her students, making it clear that she genuinely cares about the success of her students. I also like that she integrates her research into her lectures. If you ever have the opportunity, I highly recommend taking one of her courses!

rComments: Lectures were amazing and completely changed my perspective of the world. She's engaging, and you can tell she genuinely cares about being a good teacher. Dr. Frederiksen not only asks for, but responds to feedback, which in my opinion is an excellent characteristic for a professor to have. Would definitely suggest taking a class taught by her.

rComments: Expected to be bored as a 4th year taking a 1st year class, but Dr. Frederiksen was engaging. Clarified and reframed for me a lot of things I thought I already knew. Cared about teaching, not just lecturing - met students where they were at. Heavy readings for a 100-level. Could sometimes go a bit too fast, so consider recording. Overall good times
